{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Bachay ki Dua\" (\"A Child's Prayer\") captures the child's voice aspiring to a life of selfless service and enlightenment.[^1] The line that most charges the parent-child relation—evoking the fulfillment of a parent's unspoken hopes for their offspring's moral grandeur—is: \"Let my life's work be to champion the poor, / To love the weak, and those who sorrow endure.\"[^2]\n\nConversely, \"Maa ka Khwab\" (\"Mother's Dream\") unfolds from the mother's anguished perspective, dreaming of her son lagging in a procession of lamp-bearing boys, his light snuffed out by her grief.[^3] The pivotal exchange that electrifies the relation comes in the child's rebuke: \"\\\"Do you now see what has become of it? / It is your tears that have extinguished it.\\\"\"[^4] (This caps the mother's earlier lament: \"Your absence leaves me in deep turmoil; / I string each day a garland of my tears.\"[^5])\n\nThese voices dramatize parent-child bonds from reciprocal angles—the child's forward-striving prayer versus the mother's clinging sorrow—but depict **two different relationships**. Nothing in the corpus links the supplicant child of chapter 16 to the dreamed son of chapter 29; they stand as distinct vignettes in Iqbal's exploration of filial independence versus parental attachment.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 16 \"Bachay Ki Dua\" (translation), [/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-877b09](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/#p-877b09).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 \"Maa ka Khwab\" (translation), [/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/).\n\n[^4]: Ibid., [p-4feffc](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., [p-c4bed6](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-c4bed6).",
